EXO DIALECT LOWERING REFERENCE
==============================

Each op in xdsl_exo/dialects/exo.py and what it lowers to.

The steps below are ordered by recommended drop-first priority (simplest and
most independent first, most complex last). This is intentional — it does NOT
match the pipeline pass ordering in main.py. The pipeline order reflects
multi-phase lowering dependencies (early passes rewrite exo ops into
better-formed exo ops to prepare for later passes). The order here reflects
which ops are easiest to eliminate from the codebase one at a time, with each
step validated by regression tests before moving on.

STEP 1: CONSOLIDATE REWRITE FILES
====================================

After dropping the last exo op, merge rewrite files that handle
overlapping concerns. Current file layout in xdsl_exo/rewrites/:

  convert_memref_to_llvm.py — memref.AllocOp (DRAM) → malloc/free
  convert_blas.py          — VEC_AVX2 dealloc erasure + mm256_* intrinsics → vector/LLVM
  convert_avx2.py          — mm256_* intrinsics → LLVM (duplicates convert_blas.py)
  reconcile_index_casts.py — remove redundant arith.index_cast
  extended_memref_to_ptr.py — memref.cast/reinterpret_cast → ptr ops

Merge candidates:

  a) convert_avx2.py → merge into convert_blas.py
     Near-complete overlap: both handle mm256_* AVX2 intrinsic lowering.

  b) convert_blas.py + convert_memref_to_llvm.py
     Both handle memref deallocation, dispatched by memory space
     (DRAM vs VEC_AVX2). Could become a single alloc-lowering file.

Do this now that exo ops are dropped — the merges will be cleaner.

`make tests` must pass after this step. Update this TODO_EXO file to reflect
what was done (delete the completed step, renumber remaining steps).


STEP 2: SEPARATE UPSTREAM (XDSL) VS LOCAL (THIS REPO) CHANGES
===============================================================

As we make changes, we need to keep a clean separation between what gets
merged upstream into xDSL and what stays in this repository.

Upstream to xDSL: general-purpose MLIR ops and infrastructure that xDSL is
missing but MLIR has. These are things we need regardless of Exo — they just
happen to be required by our lowering. Examples:
  - memref2pointer and similar standard MLIR ops not yet in xDSL
  - Missing op variants, type support, or builder methods in existing dialects
  - Bug fixes or extensions to xDSL's core infrastructure (irdl, rewriting, etc.)

Stays in this repo: anything Exo-specific. This includes:
  - All lowering/conversion passes (convert_blas, convert_memref_to_llvm, etc.)
  - Exo-specific pipeline orchestration in main.py
  - Exo-specific test infrastructure

Rule of thumb: if the change would make sense in a codebase that has never
heard of Exo, it belongs upstream. If it only exists to support Exo's
abstractions or lowering, it stays here.

Track this throughout the refactoring — don't let upstream-worthy changes
accumulate silently in local code. File xDSL PRs as they come up.


PIPELINE ORDER (from main.py, for reference)
==============================================

This is the current pass ordering:

1. ConvertExternPass          — handle extern calls
2. ReconcileIndexCastsPass    — clean up index casts
3. ConvertBLASAllocPass       — dealloc erasure for VEC_AVX2
4. ConvertAllocFreeToLLVM     — memref.AllocOp → malloc, memref.DeallocOp → free


SUMMARY: BYPASSING EXO OPS
===========================

To generate MLIR directly and skip exo lowering entirely:

  exo.invert_window → deleted (done)
  exo.alloc         → dropped (done) — DRAM emits memref.AllocOp, VEC_AVX2 emits llvm.AllocaOp directly
  exo.read          → dropped (done) — arith.index_cast per index + memref.load (or SSA forwarding)
  exo.assign        → dropped (done) — arith.index_cast per index + memref.store (+ scalar memref wrapping)
  exo.window        → dropped (done) — stride/offset math + memref.subview with NoneAttr layout

All exo ops have been eliminated. The exo dialect (xdsl_exo/dialects/exo.py),
ConvertTensorRefPass (convert_tensor_ref.py), and ConvertMemorySpacePass
(convert_memory_space.py) have been deleted.
